2.  Project Overview

Amazon.com, Inc. processes approximately 8 million packages per day at
an estimated residential delivery cost of \$14--\$17 per package. The
proposed acquisition involves an AI-powered last-mile route optimization
platform --- exemplified by Amazon's March 2026 acquisition of RIVR, a
Zurich-based physical AI and robotics startup. The platform integrates
real-time traffic, weather, and historical delivery data to recommend
efficient routes across Amazon's 1,100+ fulfillment facilities and
200,000+ Delivery Service Partner (DSP) associates.

Last-mile delivery represents 50--60% of total parcel costs, and AI
route optimization reduces per-package costs by 10--25% at scale. The
competitive context is urgent: UPS ORION saves \$400 million per year
(14-year operational history); FedEx Surround processes 15 million
shipments daily. With FY2025 net sales of \$716.9 billion, Amazon's EU
AI Act exposure alone approaches \$50.2 billion --- making systematic
risk governance an existential financial requirement, not a compliance
formality.

3.  Revised Scoring Methodology

3.1 Recalibration Principles

The original scores were recalibrated under three principles:

Scores must reflect Amazon's actual operational context --- not generic
templates. A likelihood of 9 (≥80% probability) should only appear for
events that are near-certain given current conditions.

Root causes and resulting risks are merged into one consolidated entry.
Listing 'poor training data' and 'algorithm performance degradation' as
separate risks double-counts the same event chain and inflates the
register artificially.

Impact scores must be anchored to financial ranges. Impact 9 (Extreme,
\$5B+) is reserved for EU AI Act or equivalent existential exposures ---
not routine operational events.

