9.  Strategic Implications & Risk Governance Recommendations

Based on the revised risk register, the following governance actions are
recommended:

Establish a dedicated AI Risk Governance Committee with representation
from General Counsel, CISO, AI Ethics Board, and Data Governance ---
with authority to pause integration milestones if KRI RED thresholds are
breached.

Separate the management of AI Decision Quality risks from Cybersecurity
& Privacy risks. These are distinct failure modes requiring different
expertise, tools, and escalation paths.

Treat Algorithmic Bias & Fairness as a standalone risk category. The
consolidation of algorithmic bias, explainability, and accountability
risks into one category ensures they receive dedicated governance
attention --- not subordination under general 'Technical' risks as in
the original submission.

Budget for tail-risk events in the Low Likelihood × High Impact
quadrant. EU AI Act non-compliance (\~\$50.2B exposure) and class-action
bias litigation (\$50M--\$500M) require legal contingency funds and
modular architecture.

Maintain the heat map as a living governance document. Risk scores must
be refreshed quarterly as integration progresses and KRI data
accumulates.

Opportunities must be actively exploited --- not passively acknowledged.
The AI route efficiency opportunity (O1, Score 72) represents
\$400M--\$1.36B annual savings. Failure to exploit it is itself a risk
(captured in R26, Cost of Lagging, Score 72).

10. Conclusion

This revised report addresses all five points of Prof. Turi's feedback:
risk consolidation, opportunity separation, categorical restructuring,
score recalibration, and expanded mapping of the six highest-priority
risks. The revised register of 32 consolidated risks across 6 categories
reflects a more defensible, actionable, and academically rigorous risk
framework than the original 32-item, 6-category register which contained
duplications and calibration errors.

The revised scoring confirms 5 Very High risks (score ≥ 54), 11 High
risks (score 40--53), 13 Moderate (18--39), and 3 Low (\< 18). System
downtime (R7, score 63) and cybersecurity breach (R10, score 45) emerge
as the operationally critical risks requiring immediate mitigation
investment. EU AI Act compliance (R27, score 56) and delayed ROI (R22,
score 56) represent the strategic risks with the greatest long-term
consequence if unmanaged.

